To find the height of a flagpole, you place a mirror on the ground 
and stand where you can see the top of the flagpole in the mirror. 
You are 2 meters from the mirror, and your eyes are 1.5 meters above 
the ground. The mirror is 8 meters from the base of the flagpole. 
How tall is the flagpole?

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 % Ground
 (-1,0) – (12,0);

 % Person
 (0,0) – (0,3);
 (-0.3,2.7) – (0,3) – (0.3,2.7);
 ll[AtlasTeal] (0,3.2) circle (4pt);

 % Eye level marker
 ll[AtlasGold] (0,3) circle (3pt);
 at (-0.2,1.5) { 1.5 m};

 % Mirror
 ll[AtlasGold] (2,0) ellipse (0.3 and 0.1);
 at (2,-0.3) { mirror};

 % Flagpole
 (10,0) – (10,6);
 (10,6) – (10.5,5.5);
 at (10.2,3) {$h$};

 % Light rays
 (0,3) – (2,0) – (10,6);

 % Distance markers
 (0,-0.7) – (2,-0.7);
 at (1,-0.7) { 2 m};
 (2,-0.7) – (10,-0.7);
 at (6,-0.7) { 8 m};
tikzpicture
center

To find the width of a river, a surveyor marks points as shown. 
If $AC = 50$ m, $CD = 20$ m, and $DE = 30$ m, find the river width $AB$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.6]
 % River
 ll[blue!10] (-1,-0.5) rectangle (8,0.5);
 (-1,-0.5) – (8,-0.5);
 (-1,0.5) – (8,0.5);

 % Points
 (A) at (2,0.5);
 (B) at (2,3);
 (C) at (2,-2);
 (D) at (2,-3.5);
 (E) at (5,-3.5);

 (A) – (C);
 (C) – (D);
 (D) – (E);
 (B) – (C);
 (E) – (C);
 (A) – (B);
 (B) – (E);

 ll (A) circle (3pt);
 ll (B) circle (3pt);
 ll (C) circle (3pt);
 ll (D) circle (3pt);
 ll (E) circle (3pt);

 at (A) {$A$};
 at (B) {$B$};
 at (C) {$C$};
 at (D) {$D$};
 at (E) {$E$};

 at (2,-0.75) { 50 m};
 at (2,-2.75) { 20 m};
 at (3.5,-3.5) { 30 m};
 at (2.1,1.75) { ?};
tikzpicture
center
